The paper deals with the challenge of analyzing and discovering useful information from endless streams of text data. This suggests that the paper could belong to the Information Retrieval (cs.IR) sub-category. The paper also describes the use of semantic analysis and graph clustering techniques, which are commonly used in Natural Language Processing (NLP) and Computational Linguistics (cs.CL). The use of dynamic graph layout and Procrustes projection techniques suggests that the paper could also belong to the Scientific Computing (cs.SI) sub-category. Additionally, the paper deals with the visualization of data, which could place it in the sub-categories of Software Engineering (cs.SE) or Human-Computer Interaction (cs.HC). Finally, the use of stable component packing algorithm suggests that the paper could also belong to the sub-category of Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) or Machine Learning (cs.LG).
